data: The beautiful, adventurous and headstrong primary protagonist of the musical, dreaming of life on land instead of "under the sea". She is the youngest daughter of King Triton, and the apparent niece of Ursula.

The musical's handsome and hopeful secondary protagonist. He is destined to recover the girl that saved him from drowning, ignorant to the fact that it is Ariel, with whom he eventually falls in love.

The strict but caring father of Ariel, and ruler over Atlantica. He originally hates humans, due to the loss of his wife, causing him to commonly reprimand Ariel for her constant human explorations, but eventually realizes it is best to let her follow her dreams. He is the apparent brother of Ursula.

The musical's sinister and cunning primary antagonist. She tricks Ariel into trading her voice for a pair of human legs in order to hopefully win Prince Eric's heart, only to attempt to take advantage of Ariel's naivety. She is the apparent sister of King Triton, and aunt of Ariel.

Ariel's musical and practical guardian, Triton's faithful servant, and court composer. He serves as the musical's primary comic relief, and reluctantly assists Ariel in her efforts to charm Prince Eric.
Cody Hanford and J.J. Singleton † , Trevor Braun and Brian D'Addario
Ariel's loyal companion. He often accompanies Ariel on her excursions in search of human artifacts.

He believes he is an expert on human artifacts, although he is mainly incorrect, and is often consulted by Ariel for information on her discovered "treasures". He also serves as a comic relief, alongside Sebastian.
One of Ursula's sly and slippery henchmen.
Another one of Ursula's cunning henchmen.

Prince Eric's faithful servant and friend. Seemingly a close friend of Eric's late father, Grimsby's main initiative is to ensure that Eric marries a princess to maintain his promise to the deceased king. He realizes Ariel is a princess, and is more than happy to let them wed.
The castle chef, who tries to capture Sebastian and cook him for dinner.

Carlotta is seemingly the castle's primary maid and housekeeper. Despite the remarks of her fellow maids and servants, she is exceptionally kind to Ariel and does her best to make her feel comfortable.

title: Operator
Description
table-1565-146.caption: Arithmetic operators
data: Basic arithmetic: Addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division. In division, the right operand cannot be zero.

Increment and decrement. Increase or decrease the variable by one. These operators can be used for pre-incrementing or decrementing (as in x = ++ i), where the variable is changed before it is used in the expression. They can also be used for post-incrementing or decrementing (as in x = i++), where the value is changed after it is used in the expression. If the value of the variable i is initially 7, for example, the value of x in x = ++i is 8 after expression evaluation, but in x=i++, the value of x is 7. In both cases, the value of i becomes 8. These operators cannot be used with expressions that involve functions, as in f().a++. Also, you can use an expression such as -++x, but ---x and +++x cause errors, because their meanings are ambiguous. You can use parentheses to group the operators, as in -(--x) or +(++x), however.

Compound assignment operators. The variable on the right is used as both an element in the expression and the result variable. Thus, the expression a += b is equivalent to a = a +b. An expression can have only one compound assignment operator.
Unary arithmetic: Set the sign of a number.

Modulus: Return the remainder after a number is divided by a divisor. The result has the same sign as the divisor. The value to the right of the operator should be an integer; using a non-numeric value causes an error, and if you specify a real number, ColdFusion ignores the fractional part (for example, 11 MOD 4.7 is 3).
Integer division: Divide an integer by another integer. The result is also an integer; for example, 9\4 is 2. The right operand cannot be zero

Exponentiation: Return the result of a number raised to a power (exponent). Use the caret character (^) to separate the number from the power; for example, 2^3 is 8. Real and negative numbers are allowed for both the base and the exponent. However, any expression that equates to an imaginary number, such -1^.5 results in the string "-1.#IND. ColdFusion does not support imaginary or complex numbers.

data: Denmark is represented in Bahrain, through its embassy in Riyadh. Denmark also has a Royal Consular Agency in Manama. Bahrain is represented in Denmark, through its embassy in London.

Denmark is represented in Kuwait, through its embassy in Riyadh. Kuwait is represented in Denmark, through its embassy in Stockholm. On 6 November 2006, the Kuwaiti parliament voted 22-15 to approve severing diplomatic ties with Denmark over the Jyllands-Posten Muhammad cartoons controversy and spending about US$50 (€39.20) million to defend the prophet's image in the West. Both votes were nonbinding, meaning the Cabinet does not have to abide by them. Kuwaiti lawmaker Abdulsamad voted in favor of cutting diplomatic ties, saying, ""We have to cut diplomatic and commercial ties with Denmark...We don't have to eat Danish cheese." Al-Rashid voted against cutting diplomatic ties, arguing that Muslims have to be positive and remember that it were some individuals, not governments, who insulted the Prophet Muhammad. Al-Rashid was quoted as saying, "We here in Kuwait curse Christians in many of our mosques, should those (Christian) countries boycott Kuwait?" In February 2008, MP Abdullah Al-Roumi called for an end to Kuwait's Demark boycott and was quoted as saying, "No Muslim can accept this insult against the Prophet... It is a form of terrorism."

data: A fire in the wheel well burned through hydraulic cabling. During landing, braking was ineffective and the aircraft overran the end of the runway. After colliding with a concrete structure, the plane came to a stop. The aircraft was written off. NTSB brief

On January 16, 1990, America West flight 727 was hijacked en route to Las Vegas from Houston. The hijacker forced the pilot to land the aircraft in Austin, Texas, so it could be refueled and flown to Cuba. At the Austin airport, police overpowered and arrested the hijacker.

data: As the title suggests, it featured a copper cut-out of a '2' off of which sparks flew, as the figure glowed at its edges. This was punctuated with a loud, distinctive metallic clang sound in the audio, which overlaid a gentle, major chord pad. Edited in October 1997 but was withdrawn at the end of 1999 along with Silk, Firecracker, Diary and Steam. this ident returned on October 28th 2013 to make way for Afternoon Classics strand.

A simple ident, showing the cast shadow of a slowly rotating '2' on a viridian wall. The soundtrack shares some note similarities with Paint and Glass, albeit is not as minimal, with hints of percussion and greater variety and prominence in the chords. Withdrawn from the line-up in 1997, when the BBC corporate logo was revamped.

A subtle variation on Water, the light was altered in such a way that it cast a reflection of the water line onto the top half of the '2'. It also had the same audio as Water. This was also withdrawn before the 1997 corporate logo revamp along with four other idents.

16 February 1991 – 1 March 1991 January 1994 – October 1997 June 2001 – 19 November 2001

One of a new series of idents introduced in 1993. It featured a viridian '2' with an aerial moving about on wheels in a yellow studio, in the same manner as a remote-controlled car. The car noise varies in pitch as it whizzes around at varying speeds. It's possible that this inspired the 2001-2007 series of idents. Edited in October 1997.

One of a new series of idents introduced in 1993. It featured a viridian '2' with an aerial moving about on wheels in a yellow studio, in the same manner as a remote-controlled car. The car noise varies in pitch as it whizzes around at varying speeds. It's possible that this inspired the 2001-2007 series of idents. Edited in October 1997.

One of six new idents to be introduced at early 2000, Excalibur featured a blue '2' rising from a pool of water sideways, à la Paint. As the '2' emerges, stray droplets of water fall off the '2' and back into the water, causing (vertical) ripples, with each drop that hits the water being accompanied by a finger cymbal-esque note on the soundtrack. This ident did not feature the viridian. It was the last in this series of idents to be broadcast on BBC Two Scotland.

In this ident, liquid droplets fly in from the top right corner of the screen and cause flames to flare up around the '2' on contact. This is heralded with the sound of dramatic, blaring horns. The flames die down after about 16 seconds, revealing the 2 to be completely undamaged, before the cycle starts again. The music was later updated with the same audio as Sign along with flaring sounds.

data: Two slices of bread come out and drop onto a plate upon the '2' logo on the left side of the screen coming out. First aired 1991 and withdrawn soon after.
A cactus in a desert blooms '2' logo on the left side of the screen coming out. First aired 1991 and withdrawn soon after.
An ostrich sticks its head out of the ground upon the '2' logo on the left side of the screen coming out. First aired 1991 and withdrawn soon after.
A '2' hanging on the top of a wooden cabinet, possibly about to fall off. Introduced in 1993.
A '2' in a colourful cube crashes into the screen and gets dizzy. First aired 1995.
A '2' in a dark room, with a door being closed, leaving the '2' in darkness. There were two versions in this ident. Introduced around 1994 and usually used as a closing ident.
An egg cracks, revealing a '2' which seems like a reptile. Introduced in 1992.
A '2' jumps from a high diving board into a pool of water in a circus tent. First aired 1995.
A Slinky-shaped '2' rolls down some stairs after it presumably "sneezes". First aired 1993.
An inflatable '2' pumps on a patio, accompanied by a deep trombone piece. There was a variant where the 2 is pumped too big, and the music ends differently. First aired 1993.
A bicycle '2' does a trick, and then rides home. First aired 1993.
A '2' ball is seen in a Newton's Cradle type of toy. First aired 1994.
A black and white '2' tries to pounce on a dot. First aired 1994.
A hair drying machine opens to reveal '2' shaped hair curlers in the woman's hair First aired 1991.

One of three animated shorts featuring the duck '2', who also starred in his own ident. The '2' pops up from underneath the bubbles, and like a submarine periscope, looks around in different directions, before sinking below surface again. First aired 1997.
The second in this family of shorts. A '2' is crowded by hundreds of rubber ducks. First aired 1997.
The third in this family of shorts. This one features the duck '2' swimming through the bubble bath squeaking the theme from Jaws. First aired 1997.
The spider makes its web, and the web turns into a '2'. First aired 1995.
A saw makes a circle around the '2', causing the '2' to fall. First aired 1993.
The '2' becomes fat in a freezer after drinking too much and falls due to its weight. First aired 1998.
A 2 made of metal is picked up by a hook. First aired 1995.
A 2 colored white and black stripes blends on a same coloured background. Aired first in 1997.
A 2 shaped spacecraft lands on the moon. First aired 1994.
A grey 2 chips up a wooden floor. There was a variation where it was viewed from a top-down angle. Aired 1995.
A 2 is blown away by a boombox. Aired first 1994.
A giant 2 is rampaging in New York City which represents Stay Puft Marshmallow Man. First aired 1996.
A 2 transports via a Star Trek like device. First aired 1993.
A white 2 cuts tent supports off. First aired 2000.
A 2 dances by spinning a la ballet in a ballet classroom. First aired 2000.
A wrecking ball hits a giant 2 but cracks on impact. First aired 1994.
A 2 magnet gets everything and the camera attached to it. There was a variation with no music at all. First aired 2000.
A hair dryer dries a 2 made of cotton. First aired 1991.
A giant 2 gets a smaller one at top which that one gets a 2 which gets a 2 with a robotic camera. First aired 1998.
A 2 walks down a road then speeds off. First aired 1999.
Layers of tin foil overlap and create a 2 shape which causes the machine producing the tin foil to malfunction. First aired 1995.
A 2 spins, stops then hits a glass object making it spin again. First aired 1993.
A group of plates spinning in a 2 shape while a man tries to balance them. First aired 1992
A 2 does a dance on TV by another 2. First aired 1991
Lots of fish form a 2 before swimming off. First aired 2000.
A 2 slides down the banister and kicks the circular grip representing a "ball" into the fireplace which represents the "goal". First aired 1995.
A 2 jumps to a TV and kisses the screen. First aired 1992.
A 2 is made from snooker balls. First aired 1993.
A rusted 2 is stuck between a group of wheels. First aired 1995.
The 2 is bouncing on the TV. First aired 1999.
A snow version of Football where the 2 slides down the banisters and does a ski jump.
